       <div id="div2" class="PaddingLeft5">
        <p align="justify"></p>
        <div>
         <strong>Background</strong>
        </div> 
        <div>
         &nbsp;
        </div> 
        <div>
         Day by day business needs change depending on business requirements and fulfilling these requirements BPO and KPO come that require a physical assistance of humans to support specific requirements but some requirements exist in the application to convert text into speech without a human involved. So by considering the preceding requirement I decided to write this article.
         <br>
         <br>To convert text to speech the SpeechSynthesizer class is used. So let us learn step-by-step how to convert text to speech.
        </div> 
        <div>
         &nbsp;
        </div> 
        <div>
         <strong>The SpeechSynthesizer Class</strong>
        </div> 
        <div>
         &nbsp;
        </div> 
        <div>
         SpeechSynthesizer is a sealed class containing various methods, events and properties that help to convert text to speech with various options. The SpeechSynthesizer class is in the&nbsp;System.Speech.Synthesis namespace that contains classes that allow initialization and configuration of a speech synthesis engine, create prompts, generate speech, respond to events and modify voice characteristics. Speech synthesis is often referred to as Text-To-Speech or TTS.
        </div> 
        <div>
         &nbsp;
        </div> 
        <div>
         The following are some of the common properties of the SpeechSynthesizer class.
        </div> 
        <div>
         &nbsp;
        </div> 
        <div>
         <strong>Properties of SpeechSynthesizer class&nbsp;</strong>
        </div> 
        <div> 
         <ul> 
          <li><strong>Rate</strong>: Used to specify speech rate. </li>
          <li><strong>State</strong>: Used to check the current state of the SpeechSynthesizer class, whether it is paused, resume or a speaking state. </li>
          <li><strong>Voice</strong>: Gets the current voice information. </li>
          <li><strong>Volume</strong>: Sets the volume.</li>
         </ul> 
         <p><strong>Events of SpeechSynthesizer class&nbsp; <br></strong></p> 
         <ul> 
          <li>BookmarkReached. </li>
          <li>PhonemeReached. </li>
          <li>SpeakCompleted. </li>
          <li>SpeakProgress. </li>
          <li>SpeakStarted. </li>
          <li>StateChanged. </li>
          <li>VisemeReached. </li>
          <li>VoiceChange</li>
         </ul> 
         <p><strong>Methods of SpeechSynthesizer class </strong>&nbsp;</p> 
         <div> 
          <ul> 
           <li><span>AddLexicon&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br></span> </li>
           <li><span>Dispose &nbsp;&nbsp;</span> </li>
           <li><span>GetCurrentlySpokenPrompt</span> </li>
           <li><span>GetInstalledVoices <br></span> </li>
           <li><span>GetInstalledVoices</span> </li>
           <li><span>Pause</span> </li>
           <li><span>RemoveLexicon <br></span> </li>
           <li><span>Resume <br></span> </li>
           <li><span>SelectVoice</span> </li>
           <li><span>SelectVoiceByHints <br></span> </li>
           <li><span>SetOutputToDefaultAudioDevice</span> </li>
           <li><span>SetOutputToNull</span> </li>
           <li><span>SetOutputToWaveFile</span> </li>
           <li><span>SetOutputToWaveStream</span> </li>
           <li><span>Speak</span> </li>
           <li><span>SpeakAsync</span> </li>
           <li><span>SpeakAsyncCancel</span> </li>
           <li><span>SpeakAsyncCancelAll</span> </li>
           <li><span>SpeakSsml</span> </li>
           <li><span>SpeakSsmlAsync</span></li>
          </ul> 
          <p>Now let us see the preceding explanation by creating a sample web application as follows: </p> 
          <ol> 
           <li>"Start" - "All Programs" - "Microsoft Visual Studio 2010".<br><br> </li>
           <li>"File" - "New Project" - "C#" - "Empty WebSite" (to avoid adding a master page).<br><br> </li>
           <li>Provide the web site a name such as "TextToSppech" or another as you wish and specify the location.<br><br> </li>
           <li>Then right-click on the Solution Explorer and select "Add New Item" and Add Web Form.<br><br> </li>
           <li>Drag and drop one Button, a TextBox&nbsp; onto the &lt;form&gt; section of the Default.aspx page.</li>
          </ol> 
          <p>Now the default.aspx page source code will looks as follows.</p>
